sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1742012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Translational unit composed by the promoter 35S, the T35s terminator, the CDS Dronpa(145K), Dronpa(145N), the binding domain Gal4 and VP16. The CDS works as a toggle switch activated with green light and deactivated with blue light. Dronpa(145K) changes its conformation with light, being able to dimerize with Dronpa(145N), acting as a transcription factor.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: M??nica Victoria Guti??rrez Salazar
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Do a PCR to obtain the Dronpa(145N)

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1467101
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
35S is a plant specific promoter obtained from Cauliflower Mosaic Virus. The part is intended for use as a constitutive promoter for gene expression experiments.
The part is compatible with GoldenGate MoClo Assembly Standard (free from BsaI and BpiI recognition sequences).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Cara Deal
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Domestication for GoldenGate (Removal of internal BsaI and BpiI recognition sequences).

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K105007
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Gal4 is a yeast transcription factor which activates the transcription.<br\n>
This BioBrick is the DNA binding domain of Gal4, which binds specificly to the regulatory sequence [[Part:BBa_K105024| BBa_K105024]].
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Katja Karstens
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
To enable the fusion with other domains in frame the vector of this BioBrick has no base pair in between the restriction side and the BioBrick. Furthermore, this coding sequence does not include a start codon.
For more information about this issus, see:
Phillips, I.E. and Silver, P.A. "A new Biobrick Assembly Strategy Designed for Facile Protein Engineering."
DSpace http://hdl.handle.net/1721.1/32535 (2006).

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K105001
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Originally VP16 is a protein from the herpes simplex virus. It activates the transcription of the late genes of this virus by the RNA-polymerase II of the eucaryotic host.
In artificial systems VP16 is used in fusion with a DNA-binding domain. This DNA-binding domain is specific for a bait sequence. So the selective expression of genes with a promoter containing this bait sequence can be achieved.
